          "[8]  In the 10 days following a beach visit, 21% of diarrhea episodes were attributed to swimming in contaminated waters. The risk of diarrhea was higher for those exposed to levels of Enterococcus (an indicator of human fecal contamination) above the US EPA's regulatory guidelines for beaches. Associations between water quality and illness were even stronger for children under 10. This age group spent more time in the water on average, and had a higher likelihood of swallowing water. Children age 0-4 who were exposed to waters not meeting EPA's Recreational Water Quality Criteria had twice the risk of diarrhea compared with those who did not swim (aCIR 2.00, 95% CI 1.38, 2.91) (<a href=\"https://awseastaging.epa.gov/EcoHealthBrowser/bibliography.html#Arnold_2016\" target=\"_blank\">Arnold et al., 2016</a>; n=84,411, USA).",
